fields.title: The OncoTime Programming Language
fields.content:
Introduction

The OncoTime Programming language was designed by professor Laurie Hendren as a solution to problems faced by doctors in the Radiation Oncology laboratory at the Montreal General Hospital. The hospital had a program, wherein Doctor, Patient, and Diagnosis data was all stored in a MySQl database. The issue was that Doctors, not trained in programming or database querying, found it very difficult to access the data and information they needed. OncoTime acted as a solution.

OncoTime is a general purpose, "wrapper" language that allows users to quickly write simply programs that will allow them access to the information they need, quickly, and efficiently. It was written in the C Programming Language using Flex / Bison My team developed the otc OncoTime compiler which took OncoTime programs and created Python code that would access and display the results of the MySQL queries to the user.

We were able to create great graphs to make it easier for doctors

We are currently in the process of making the source code available unders and open source license. The idea being that we want everyone to have access to the OncoTime language, as well as allow intelligent developers to help us further develop the language.

Looking Forward

We want to continue to develop and work on OncoTime. As such, I will be working with Laurie this summer to create a Web interface for OncoTime, wherein which potential users don't have to learn the language to get access to the data. I think this will be a great step forward for OncoTime and for the users at the Hospital, who an continue to improve patient care by getting access to the information they need.

fields.title: My Summer Projects at Microsoft
fields.content:
Introduction

Last Summer I was fortunate enough to be a Summer intern at Microsoft. (Now, that in itself was an experience, and I urge you to take a look at my article detailing my experiences). The Summer was particularily interesting because I had the chance to develop two great apps that helped us get a better understanding of the Highlights and Pain Points facing developers who wish to develop on the new Universal Application Development Environment.

In this article, I wanted to give you a quick idea of what the two applications did, so as to provide you with a better understanding of the sorts of work I did this last Summer.

Open States

I developed the first application in order to get a better understanding of how difficult it would be to port an application from iOS to Windows. As such, I chose the Open States iOS application.

The concept behind OpenStates was simple enough. The application pulls data from Sun Light Labs, Open States API. The data regarding Politicians, their constiuencies, and their policies, are then displayed to the user in the iOS app.

The original OpenStates app. Taken from iTunes

For my part, I developed a Universal Application using the C# Programming Language and the Universal Application Framework. The final product was then demonstrated to my team, and I wrote a report detailing my experiences. Unfortunately, the information contained in that report is not available for the public.

Recipe Guide

The second application was developed in order to test Apache Cordova. This absolutely wonderful tool allows developers to write one single application in HTML/CSS and Javascript , and then deploy that app on a wide variety of mobile and tablet form factors.

Yummly is a great tool to get information about recipes

Recipe Guide, the application I built, simply got information from Yummly and displayed the information to the user. The actual application allowed users to have profiles, store favourite recipes, create grocery lists from recipies, and view the nutritional and taste information. I wrote the application using HTML/CSS and Javascript and deployed it on a variety of form factors, including multiple Windows phone devices, an iPhone, and an Android Tablet.

Looking Forward

I am pleased to be returning back to Microsoft in the Fall to continue my work on improving the developer experience. I will be working with the Universal Applications Team as a Software Development Engineer in Seattle, WA.

fields.title: Asteria: Battle for the Frontier
fields.content:
Introduction

Many Computer Science programs have students creating a large scale applicaiton at the end of their program. For me, that was Asteria: Battle for the Frontier.

The project (a team based activity, which posed it's own difficulties) was to build a game using any language and any libraries we chose. This article outlines the details of the project.

The Game

The start page for Asteria: Battle for the Frontier

Asteria: Battle for the Frontier is a real time, online multiplayer, strategy game. Players are matched up in real time with other players from around the world. Each player has an assortment of 7 ships (2 Destroyers, 2 MineLayers, 2 Cruisers, 1 Gunboat) The game begins with the players selecting where they would like to place their ships. Once all the ships have been placed, the action begins!

Players must control their ships, each with varying speeds and capabilities, and attack and destroy either all the opponents ships, or their base. If a players ship is damaged, it can retreat back to the base in order to heal itself. Moreover, proximity mines can be laid that upon notification that a ship (enemy or friendly) is next to a mine, detonates damaging all ships in the surrounding area.

The Technical Details

Firstly, it should be noted that the source code is available, open source, at Github. Feel free to take a look.

The progam was written entirely in Java using the LibGDX development environment. We wrote the networking ourselves, using Java Sockets in order to transfer data. Moreover, we wrote the code for the server, that handled the majority of the game logic. This meant that players computers simply needed to have access to the graphics rendering code, meaning their own overhead was very low. Since the game was rendered in 2D using simple Geometric Shapes, the overhead on any one computer was quite low. This meant that the bottleneck, if any, would occur on the server, meaning both players would be affected equally, thus limiting the implications on gameplay.

If anyone wants to learn about LibGDX game development, I strongly urge them to check out Learning LibGDX Game Development by Andreas Oehike. This is the book we chose to use and it definitely made our lives easier.

fields.title: The Five Things Every Developer Should Do
fields.content:
(1) Read, Read, Read

It's a little ironic that I should be writing this number 1 'do' because I switched from the Humanities to Computer Science because I was tired of reading. The fact remains though, that technology is always changing and evolving. We developers and engineers can't afford not to keep up with the latest developments and news. With respect to getting developer news, its as easy as spending 15 minutes on HackerNews or /r/Programming

It is also important the developers and engineers keep reading about what facinates them in their particular field. For example, I am very interested in Compiler Design, so I am currently making my way through Crafting a Compiler. This way, not only am I staying passionate about my field, but I am also increasing my worth as a developer by increasing the knowledge I have.

(2) Write, Write, Write

Know something not very many people know about? Share it with the world! Not only does writing (or abstracted, teaching) help solidify your own knowledge, you could be providing a resource that many people are looking for. Have you had a summer internship at a high profile company? Write about your experiences interviewing and working their. Did you work on a really cool project, using hot new technologies? Write about how those technologies worked and how your project worked. The possibilites are endless.

Not only does writing help the reader, it also helps you. Imagine you were working on a project and didn't understand a topic. You found a great blog article explaining that topic clearly, and simply. Maybe you want the guy or gal who wrote that article on your team! This happens all the time, in a field where technical expertise are so highly valued, companies will work day and night to get developers who have shown their skills through blogs and other written sources.

(3) Contribute to Open Source Code

Much in the same light as the previous point, contributing to open source code is a great way to increase your knowledge as a developer, while simultaneously getting your name out there. If you contribute to a variety of projects you will quickly build experience that will help on the job.

Moreoer, Open Source projects are a great way to contribute back to the community. The projects provide free services that thousands of people can use, irrespective of whether they are developers or not. You may even find that the deeper you get into the open source community, the more interesting projects you find.

(4) Ask Questions

if you don't understand something, ask someone who does. This conept is not overly difficult, but I find many developers will often be afraid of looking stupid or incompetent if they ask a question. It's important to know that no project can be completed without help and that you are hurting the project by not asking questions and making assumptions

(5) Work in Teams

Finally, it is important to recognize that no developer works by themselves. The idea that Comptuer Scientists are reclusive individuals who huddle away in dark basements working on technical projects is far flung from reality. You will find yourself working in teams more often then not, and only very rarely will you have a piece of code you wrote entirely by yourself. Work in teams, get used to working in teams, and learn what makes a team thrive.

You will be a better developer for it.
